{"title_page": "1904 Harvard Crimson football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1904\n| team = Harvard Crimson\n| image = Harvard Crimson logo.svg\n| image_size = 100\n| conference = Independent\n| record = 7\u20132\u20131\n| head_coach = [[Edgar Wrightington]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = [[Daniel Hurley (American football)|Daniel Hurley]]\n| stadium = [[Harvard Stadium]]\n}}\n{{1904 Eastern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1904 Harvard Crimson football team''' represented [[Harvard University]] in the [[1903 college football season]]. The Crimson finished with a 7\u20132\u20131 record under first-year head coach [[Edgar Wrightington]].<ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=1904 Harvard Crimson Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=February 27, 2017|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/harvard/1904-schedule.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gocrimson.com/sports/fball/history/Media_Center_Football_Yearly_Results |title=Harvard Football Yearly Records|work=GoCrimson.com |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>  [[Walter Camp]] selected only one Harvard player, halfback [[Daniel Hurley (American football)|Daniel Hurley]], as a first-team selection to his [[1904 College Football All-America Team]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Camp's Idea Of Football Stars: Yale Coach Puts Two Western Men in His Selection|work=The Daily Review (Decatur, IL)|date=1904-12-28}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n\n{{CFB schedule\n|September 28| |{{cfb link|year=1904|team=Williams Ephs|title=Williams}}|[[Harvard Stadium]]|[[Boston|Boston, MA]]|W 24\u20130\n\n|October 5| |{{cfb link|year=1904|team=Bowdoin Polar Bears|title=Bowdoin}}|Harvard Stadium|Boston, MA|W 17\u20130\n\n|October 8| |{{cfb link|year=1904|team=Maine Black Bears|title=Maine}}|Harvard Stadium|Boston, M