{"title_page": "Theo Verschueren", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Theo Verschueren 1966.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n|caption=Theo Verschueren in 1966\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1943|1|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Sint Jansteen]], [[Netherlands]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n| height = \n| weight = \n|sport=[[Motor-paced racing]]\n|club=\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{BEL}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Motor-paced World Championships|Motor-paced World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|1969 Brno|Professionals}}\n{{MedalSilver|1970 Leicester|Professionals}}\n{{MedalGold|1971 Varese|Professionals}}\n{{MedalGold|1972 Marseille|Professionals}}\n{{MedalSilver|1974 Montreal|Professionals}}\n}}\n'''Theo Verschueren''' (born 27 January 1943) is a retired Belgian cyclist. He had his best achievements in [[motor-paced racing]], in which he won the [[UCI Motor-paced World Championships|world championships]] in the professionals category in 1971 and 1972 and finished second in 1969, 1970 and 1974. During his career Verschueren took part in 67 [[Six-day racing|six-day road races]], winning the race of Antwerp in 1968 and 1972.<ref name=r1/> \n\nHe married the daughter of Belgian cyclist [[Petrus Van Theemsche]].<ref name=r1/> He is not related to [[Adolph Verschueren]], another motor-paced racing world champion from Belgium.\n\n==Teams==\n* 1963-1965: Dr.Mann\n* 1966-1967: Romeo Smith\u2019s\n* 1968-1969: Goldor-Gerka\n* 1970-1971: Hertekamp-Magniflex\n* 1972-1973: Rokado\n* 1974: MIC-Ludo-De Gribaldy\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.radsportseiten.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8050 Theo Verschueren]. radsportseiten.net</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verschueren, Theo}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Hulst]]\n[[Category:UCI Track Cycling World Champions (men)]]\n[[Category:Belgian track cyclists]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Theo Verschueren 1966.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n|caption=Theo Verschueren in 1966\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1943|1|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Sint Jansteen]], [[Netherlands]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n| height = \n| weight = \n|sport=[[Motor-paced racing]]\n|club=\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{BEL}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Motor-paced World Championships|Motor-paced World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|1969 Brno|Professionals}}\n{{MedalSilver|1970 Leicester|Professionals}}\n{{MedalGold|1971 Varese|Professionals}}\n{{MedalGold|1972 Marseille|Professionals}}\n{{MedalSilver|1974 Montreal|Professionals}}\n}}\n'''Theo Verschueren''' (born 27 January 1943) is a retired Belgian cyclist. He had his best achievements in [[motor-paced racing]], in which he won the [[UCI Motor-paced World Championships|world championships]] in the professionals category in 1971 and 1972 and finished second in 1969, 1970 and 1974. During his career Verschueren took part in 67 [[Six-day racing|six-day road races]], winning the race of Antwerp in 1968 and 1972.<ref name=r1/> \n\nHe married the daughter of Belgian cyclist [[Petrus Van Theemsche]].<ref name=r1/> He is not related to [[Adolph Verschueren]], another motor-paced racing world champion from Belgium.\n\n==Teams==\n* 1963-1965: Dr.Mann\n* 1966-1967: Romeo Smith\u2019s\n* 1968-1969: Goldor-Gerka\n* 1970-1971: Hertekamp-Magniflex\n* 1972-1973: Rokado\n* 1974: MIC-Ludo-De Gribaldy\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.radsportseiten.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8050 Theo Verschueren]. radsportseiten.net</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verschueren, Theo}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Hulst]]\n[[Category:UCI Track Cycling World Champions (men)]]\n