ank Fact File for the United States Army]\n* [http://www.armyrecognition.com/united_states_army_heavy_armoured_vehicles_tank_uk/m1a1_abrams_main_battle_tank_technical_data_sheet_specifications_description_pictures_video.html M1A1 main battle tank on armyrecognition.com]\n* [http://people.howstuffworks.com/m1-tank.htm M1 Abrams page, with a detailed overview of how the tank works on howstuffworks.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060819143950/http://www.defense-update.com/products/t/tusk.htm M1 Tank Urban Survivability Kit (TUSK)], [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011072821/http://defense-update.com/products/m/M1A1AIM.htm M1A1 AIM Upgrade], and [https://web.archive.org/web/20070210172647/http://www.defense-update.com/products/m/M1A2SEP.htm M1A2 SEP Upgrade on Defense-Update.com]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ground/m1-intro.htm M1 Abrams Main Battle Tank page on GlobalSecurity.org]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160909103204/http://www51.honeywell.com/aero/common/documents/myaerospacecatalog-documents/SurfaceSystems/AGT1500_Turbine_Technology.pdf AGT1500 Turbine Technology on Honeywell.com]\n* [http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/M1-Abrams-Tanks-for-Iraq-05013/ M1 Abrams Tanks for Iraq]\n* [http://armour.ws/m1a2-abrams-tank/ M1A2 on Armour.ws]\n* [http://www.fprado.com/armorsite/abrams.htm M1A1/2 Abrams page on the Armor Site]\n* [http://www.enemyforces.com/tanks/m1a1abrams.htm Main Battle Tank M1A1 Abrams on Enemyforces.com]\n* [https://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/wsh2010/16.pdf M1 Abrams modernisation 2011]\n* [https://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/wsh2011/16.pdf M1 Abrams modernisation 2012]\n\n{{General Dynamics}}\n{{Post-Cold War tanks|style=wide}}\n\n[[Category:Cold War tanks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Main battle tanks of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Main battle tanks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Military vehicles introduced in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:General Dynamics land vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "86.18.186.78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M1_Abrams"}
{"title_page": "Nduka Odizor", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian tennis player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name= Nduka Odizor\n|image=\n|country= {{NGR}}\n|residence=\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1958|8|9|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n|height= {{height|m=1.82|precision=0}}\n|turnedpro=\n|plays= Right-handed (one-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney= $675,673\n|singlesrecord= 82\u2013124\n|singlestitles= 1\n|highestsinglesranking= No. 52 (11 June 1984)\n|AustralianOpenresult= 3R (1985)\n|FrenchOpenresult= 1R (1986)\n|Wimbledonresult= 4R (1983)\n|USOpenresult= 3R (1985, 1987)\n|doublesrecord= 137\u2013138\n|doublestitles= 7\n|highestdoublesranking= No. 20 (27 August 1984)\n|updated=\n}}\n\n'''Nduka Odizor''' (born 28 August 1958) is a former [[tennis player]] from [[Nigeria]], who represented his native country at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]], where he was defeated in the first round by [[United States|American]] lucky loser [[Robert Seguso]]. The right-hander won one career title in singles ([[Taipei]], 1983) and seven doubles titles. He reached his highest [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] singles ranking of World No. 52 in June 1984.\n\n==Career finals==\n===Doubles (7 wins, 4 losses)===\n{|class=wikitable \n!width=80|Outcome\n!width=40|No.\n!width=50|Date\n!width=200|Tournament\n!width=75|Surface\n!width=200|Partner\n!width=200|Opponents in the final\n!width=125|Score in the final\n|-\n|-\n| bgcolor=98FB98|Winner\n| 1.\n| 1983\n| [[Monterrey|Monterrey, Mexico]]\n| Carpet\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[David Dowlen]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Andy Andrews (tennis player)|Andy Andrews]] <br> {{flagicon|USA}} [[John Sadri]]\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20133, 6\u20134\n|-\n| bgcolor=98FB98|Winner\n| 2.\n| 1983\n| [[Dallas Open (tennis)|Dallas, U.S.]]\n| Hard\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Van Winitsky]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Denton]